00:02:48.620 --> 00:02:52.070
put to this commission was
to feed the world a diet that

00:02:52.070 --> 00:02:55.490
is healthy and
sustainable, and by 2050,

00:02:55.490 --> 00:02:58.160
will reach close to
10 billion people.

00:02:58.160 --> 00:03:01.280
And as you said, we're
currently far off track

00:03:01.280 --> 00:03:04.260
from arriving at that goal.

00:03:04.260 --> 00:03:10.020
Therefore, the commission really
faced a tremendous challenge.

00:03:10.020 --> 00:03:12.920
In fact, just to
paint a quick picture,

00:03:12.920 --> 00:03:15.810
if we look at the nutritional
status of the world,

00:03:15.810 --> 00:03:17.780
it's not a pretty picture.

00:03:17.780 --> 00:03:20.630
We have, still, about
800 million people

00:03:20.630 --> 00:03:22.040
who are undernourished.

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:26.030
We have about 2 billion people
who are overweight or obese,

00:03:26.030 --> 00:03:31.170
and that number is increasing
rapidly all around the world.

00:03:31.170 --> 00:03:33.050
And most of the
rest of the world

00:03:33.050 --> 00:03:35.870
is eating a diet that's
far from optimal.

00:03:35.870 --> 00:03:38.750
And to make it more
complicated, as you also

00:03:38.750 --> 00:03:40.460
noticed, the way
we produce our food

00:03:40.460 --> 00:03:42.650
and the way we produce
what we're eating today

00:03:42.650 --> 00:03:44.630
is degrading the
planet, and really

00:03:44.630 --> 00:03:46.310
undermining the
resources that are

00:03:46.310 --> 00:03:50.960
critical to feed the future
population of the world.

00:03:50.960 --> 00:03:54.920
And then we are adding close
to 2 and 1/2 billion people

00:03:54.920 --> 00:03:57.630
by 2050.

00:03:57.630 --> 00:03:59.450
That's a pretty
daunting challenge,

00:03:59.450 --> 00:04:02.570
given that, to arrive at a
sustainable and healthy diet

00:04:02.570 --> 00:04:03.860
for everyone.

00:04:03.860 --> 00:04:08.390
So to get at this issue,
we broke the process down

00:04:08.390 --> 00:04:09.930
into several steps.

00:04:09.930 --> 00:04:13.850
The first was to, using
the best available evidence

00:04:13.850 --> 00:04:18.350
from all around the world, to
define what is a healthy diet.

00:04:18.350 --> 00:04:21.470
And I can't go into all
of the details of that,

00:04:21.470 --> 00:04:27.770
but if I could have a slide up,
basically, what we realized,

00:04:27.770 --> 00:04:29.630
putting all the
evidence together,

00:04:29.630 --> 00:04:32.610
was that there's quite
a bit of flexibility.

00:04:32.610 --> 00:04:35.510
And this allows a lot
of diversity of diets

00:04:35.510 --> 00:04:39.320
from different cultures,
different agricultural systems,

00:04:39.320 --> 00:04:42.770
but primarily this will
mean a substantial shift

00:04:42.770 --> 00:04:46.040
from what we're doing today,
to a diet that is largely

00:04:46.040 --> 00:04:51.920
plant based, but still has some
meat, some dairy, fish in it.

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:59.060
And plenty of healthy foods
in the diet, more nuts, more

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:03.350
fruits, vegetables, legumes,
and the amount of fish

00:05:03.350 --> 00:05:07.280
would increase, given from
what we are doing today.

00:05:07.280 --> 00:05:11.810
Very briefly, this slide
shows the major food groups,

00:05:11.810 --> 00:05:15.620
and the vertical line toward
the left of that figure

00:05:15.620 --> 00:05:19.640
is, essentially, the target
numbers that we came up with

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:22.340
to define an optimally
healthy diet.

00:05:22.340 --> 00:05:26.150
And then the various
bars indicate

00:05:26.150 --> 00:05:28.710
what different regions of
the world are eating today.

00:05:28.710 --> 00:05:31.880
And as you can see, we're
in general, quite a bit

00:05:31.880 --> 00:05:33.887
over the target
numbers for red meat,

00:05:33.887 --> 00:05:35.970
but that's very different
for different countries.

00:05:35.970 --> 00:05:39.150
Southeast Asia, for example,
is below the target number.

00:05:39.150 --> 00:05:41.250
So there's a lot of variability.

00:05:41.250 --> 00:05:43.160
But toward the
bottom, we see again

00:05:43.160 --> 00:05:47.310
that the healthy foods fruits,
nuts, legumes, soy products,

00:05:47.310 --> 00:05:52.460
nuts where we would be better
off with substantial increases.

00:05:52.460 --> 00:05:55.310
We use several
different approaches

00:05:55.310 --> 00:05:58.010
to evaluate the
healthfulness of this diet,

00:05:58.010 --> 00:06:03.530
and they all converge to just
that if we did, our world, move

00:06:03.530 --> 00:06:05.900
to this these
dietary targets, we

00:06:05.900 --> 00:06:09.090
would prevent about 11 million
premature deaths per year,

00:06:09.090 --> 00:06:13.380
which is about 20% to 25% of
the total deaths for a year.

00:06:13.380 --> 00:06:18.170
So there's a huge health benefit
of adopting this healthy diet.

00:06:18.170 --> 00:06:19.880
We then, as a
second step, went on

00:06:19.880 --> 00:06:22.670
to look at whether
we could possibly

00:06:22.670 --> 00:06:25.520
produce this diet within
the planetary boundaries.

00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:28.370
We can't infinitely produce
more greenhouse gas,

00:06:28.370 --> 00:06:30.080
use unlimited amounts of water.

00:06:30.080 --> 00:06:33.620
There are planetary
boundaries that

00:06:33.620 --> 00:06:37.130
have been defined by
other research groups.

00:06:37.130 --> 00:06:40.460
And the good news is when
we went through all of this,

00:06:40.460 --> 00:06:43.850
that it is possible to feed the
world a healthy and sustainable

00:06:43.850 --> 00:06:47.480
diet by 2050, but it will
require major changes

00:06:47.480 --> 00:06:49.525
in what we eat, and how
we produce our food.

