I, full disclosure, started
my career at Microsoft,

00:26:35.123 --> 00:26:37.540
and so I'm going to mention a
project from them, because I

00:26:37.540 --> 00:26:38.560
know the company well.

00:26:38.560 --> 00:26:41.520
It's called FarmBeats.

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:44.390
FarmBeats, have you ever
turned on your television,

00:26:44.390 --> 00:26:47.798
I know some of us on this panel
do know what I'm talking about.

00:26:47.798 --> 00:26:49.840
You turn on the television,
and there's a channel

00:26:49.840 --> 00:26:51.760
that's just whitespace.

00:26:51.760 --> 00:26:55.040
Well those white spaces
exist all over the place,

00:26:55.040 --> 00:26:56.830
including on farms.

00:26:56.830 --> 00:27:02.240
That sort of television space
is available and underutilized.

00:27:02.240 --> 00:27:04.120
So there's a project
that Microsoft

00:27:04.120 --> 00:27:06.970
is leading through
their AI for Earth,

00:27:06.970 --> 00:27:09.640
Artificial Intelligence
for Earth project,

00:27:09.640 --> 00:27:12.190
around the internet of
things to try and capture

00:27:12.190 --> 00:27:14.950
that white space
and use it on farm.

00:27:14.950 --> 00:27:18.670
And so you can imagine, a
drone if you can afford it,

00:27:18.670 --> 00:27:20.410
but a helium balloon
if you can't,

00:27:20.410 --> 00:27:23.560
that takes a mobile phone
up, gets a view of the farm,

00:27:23.560 --> 00:27:25.960
sends the data up
into the cloud,

00:27:25.960 --> 00:27:27.822
and gets it right back
to you, very quickly,

00:27:27.822 --> 00:27:30.280
with real time data that you
can use to look at your field.

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:32.860
What's over-watered,
what's underwatered.

00:27:32.860 --> 00:27:35.260
Where are the pests,
where aren't the pests.

00:27:35.260 --> 00:27:37.330
And that's being tested
right now by Microsoft

00:27:37.330 --> 00:27:40.040
in places like Carnation
Washington and in other places.

00:27:40.040 --> 00:27:43.177
So really interesting sort of
things that some of our member

00:27:43.177 --> 00:27:45.760
companies are doing, and others
that are nonmembers are doing,

00:27:45.760 --> 00:27:47.530
and I just thought I'd
tee some of those up

00:27:47.530 --> 00:27:48.905
DAVID FREEMAN:
Yeah, interesting.

00:27:48.905 --> 00:27:51.670
So and Gina, we're talking about
this kind of high technology,

00:27:51.670 --> 00:27:53.800
but also what can you
tell us about better ways

00:27:53.800 --> 00:27:55.750
to use the agricultural
land that we do?

00:27:55.750 --> 00:27:58.610
What are some things that
we need to do with the land?

00:27:58.610 --> 00:28:02.170
GINA MCCARTHY: Well let
me begin by saying, Ana,

00:28:02.170 --> 00:28:05.740
you might think that we are
out to change the world,

00:28:05.740 --> 00:28:08.340
but you rock my world.

00:28:08.340 --> 00:28:12.160
I'm telling you, your food
experienced is quite amazing.

00:28:12.160 --> 00:28:13.080
So thank your husband.

00:28:13.080 --> 00:28:16.440
I had no idea it was part of it.

00:28:16.440 --> 00:28:18.810
Part of the challenge
that we face

00:28:18.810 --> 00:28:21.720
is that agriculture
today, at least

00:28:21.720 --> 00:28:23.670
the way the majority
of it is practiced,

00:28:23.670 --> 00:28:27.010
it can be considerably
damaging to the environment.

00:28:27.010 --> 00:28:27.780
I mean, we see it.

00:28:27.780 --> 00:28:31.770
We see the harmful algal blooms
that are just about everywhere

00:28:31.770 --> 00:28:33.180
across the United States.

00:28:33.180 --> 00:28:35.280
Most notably, we
saw it in Toledo,

00:28:35.280 --> 00:28:38.580
where they had
cyanotoxins created

00:28:38.580 --> 00:28:40.920
by harmful algal
blooms, that were really

00:28:40.920 --> 00:28:44.400
a result of runoff that
went into Western Lake Erie,

00:28:44.400 --> 00:28:46.780
and where the water gets
warmer and climate change,

00:28:46.780 --> 00:28:48.180
those things happen.

00:28:48.180 --> 00:28:51.120
And we have to think about
keeping soil in its place.

00:28:51.120 --> 00:28:53.970
So every time you
till for farming,

00:28:53.970 --> 00:28:58.600
you have the challenge of
increasing carbon emissions,

00:28:58.600 --> 00:29:00.240
and you have the
challenge of runoff,

00:29:00.240 --> 00:29:02.850
that right now even
in the United States,

00:29:02.850 --> 00:29:05.850
55% of the river
and stream miles

00:29:05.850 --> 00:29:08.100
are actually too
heavily contaminated

00:29:08.100 --> 00:29:11.130
with nutrients from
runoff to be able to have

00:29:11.130 --> 00:29:12.840
healthy ecosystems.

00:29:12.840 --> 00:29:14.880
So for many reasons
we need to change

00:29:14.880 --> 00:29:16.350
the way we think about it.

00:29:16.350 --> 00:29:18.240
We need to store the
carbon in the soil.

00:29:18.240 --> 00:29:21.090
Soil is everything.

00:29:21.090 --> 00:29:23.250
I think people have
always known this,

00:29:23.250 --> 00:29:27.360
and we have to recognize that
with the exacerbated storms

00:29:27.360 --> 00:29:29.880
that we're seeing with
a changing climate is

00:29:29.880 --> 00:29:31.500
you have to plan for runoff.

00:29:31.500 --> 00:29:33.540
You have to think
about how you use

00:29:33.540 --> 00:29:35.340
no till farming where you can.

00:29:35.340 --> 00:29:39.210
You have to think about how you
use the kind of technologies

00:29:39.210 --> 00:29:42.480
you're talking about to be able
to understand where water needs

00:29:42.480 --> 00:29:44.250
to be used and
where it's wasted.

00:29:44.250 --> 00:29:46.560
Because water is going to
compete between drinking

00:29:46.560 --> 00:29:48.720
water and feeding people.

00:29:48.720 --> 00:29:53.050
That's a competition we don't
want either side to lose.

00:29:53.050 --> 00:29:54.480
And so there are
ways in which we

00:29:54.480 --> 00:29:57.660
have to think about
feeding more people,

00:29:57.660 --> 00:30:00.390
but making our
ability to produce

00:30:00.390 --> 00:30:06.150
that an opportunity to
reduce the current impacts,

00:30:06.150 --> 00:30:09.090
and an opportunity to reduce
the methane and greenhouse

00:30:09.090 --> 00:30:12.930
gases that are being emitted,
without eliminating the best

00:30:12.930 --> 00:30:16.000
foods that are available
and nutritious for us.

00:30:16.000 --> 00:30:18.960
And I think it's a challenge,
but I think by no means

00:30:18.960 --> 00:30:21.060
is it an insurmountable one.

00:30:21.060 --> 00:30:23.340
We have regenerative
agriculture that

00:30:23.340 --> 00:30:27.420
is all about policies and
practices that do exactly this.

00:30:27.420 --> 00:30:31.590
That use natural systems,
ecosystems, biodiversity,

00:30:31.590 --> 00:30:34.740
instead of looking at
dead end use of chemicals,

00:30:34.740 --> 00:30:37.350
where they have nowhere
to go, but in our food

00:30:37.350 --> 00:30:38.890
or in our water.

00:30:38.890 --> 00:30:41.130
And so there are ways
in which this is already

00:30:41.130 --> 00:30:45.450
being explored, successfully,
in so many places.

00:30:45.450 --> 00:30:48.280
The issue is how do
we scale that up.

00:30:48.280 --> 00:30:49.500
How do we spread the word.

00:30:49.500 --> 00:30:53.760
How do we change the
equation for agriculture

00:30:53.760 --> 00:30:57.450
to shift from being a carbon
emitter to being a carbon

00:30:57.450 --> 00:31:00.180
sink, which could make
them opportunities

00:31:00.180 --> 00:31:05.520
for significant resources as
we start really valuing carbon

00:31:05.520 --> 00:31:07.800
emissions and put
a price on carbon,

00:31:07.800 --> 00:31:10.860
the way I think everybody
knows and expects will happen.

00:31:10.860 --> 00:31:13.260
So there's opportunities
for agriculture

00:31:13.260 --> 00:31:16.110
to do what they do best,
which is to protect the land

00:31:16.110 --> 00:31:18.750
and produce our food,
and do it in a way that

00:31:18.750 --> 00:31:22.890
makes them more economically
viable at the same time.

00:31:22.890 --> 00:31:25.952
And that's the win
that we have to go for.

00:31:25.952 --> 00:31:27.660
DAVID FREEMAN: Well,
