00:38:58.350 --> 00:39:00.270
the gap between rich and poor.

00:39:00.270 --> 00:39:02.820
So I wonder if you
can tell us about how

00:39:02.820 --> 00:39:08.430
the UN is trying to, using
the SDGs, to prevent that

00:39:08.430 --> 00:39:10.265
from happening and
getting any worse?

00:39:10.265 --> 00:39:11.640
DAVID BENNELL:
Well, first of all

00:39:11.640 --> 00:39:13.432
I live in Maine so
thanks for the shout out

00:39:13.432 --> 00:39:15.690
to Maine lobster, Walter.

00:39:15.690 --> 00:39:17.880
We appreciate it.

00:39:17.880 --> 00:39:19.690
I mean, WBCSD
looks at everything

00:39:19.690 --> 00:39:21.690
we do through the Sustainable
Development Goals.

00:39:21.690 --> 00:39:25.090
So if you have not ever
heard of them, that's OK.

00:39:25.090 --> 00:39:30.780
You're normal, but it
really is a powerful--

00:39:30.780 --> 00:39:33.570
it's a license to
operate on this Earth.

00:39:33.570 --> 00:39:35.700
So take a look at it.

00:39:35.700 --> 00:39:39.600
SDG2 Two, zero
hunger, is where I've

00:39:39.600 --> 00:39:44.400
spent a good portion of this
week working in Washington DC.

00:39:44.400 --> 00:39:47.190
So if you look at SDG
Two on zero hunger,

00:39:47.190 --> 00:39:49.830
and you start to look at the
targets and the initiatives,

00:39:49.830 --> 00:39:51.330
you'll find it
really drills down

00:39:51.330 --> 00:39:54.720
to things like gender,
and climate change,

00:39:54.720 --> 00:39:56.860
and sustainable
consumption and production.

00:39:56.860 --> 00:40:00.270
Gina, very rightly
mentioned a huge amount

00:40:00.270 --> 00:40:01.290
of food loss and waste.

00:40:01.290 --> 00:40:03.405
If food loss and
waste were a country,

00:40:03.405 --> 00:40:05.280
it would be about the
third or fourth largest

00:40:05.280 --> 00:40:08.430
emitter of greenhouse gas
emissions in the world.

00:40:08.430 --> 00:40:10.230
So I mean there's so
much wrapped up just

00:40:10.230 --> 00:40:12.090
in the idea of zero hunger.

00:40:12.090 --> 00:40:15.150
We have a program called
FRESH, which Walter knows well,

00:40:15.150 --> 00:40:18.000
Food Reform for
Sustainability in Health.

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:21.240
And one of the work streams in
there, early on, was focused

00:40:21.240 --> 00:40:23.347
on nutrition and security.

00:40:23.347 --> 00:40:25.680
Some of the most nutrition
insecure people in the world,

00:40:25.680 --> 00:40:29.200
paradoxically and
sadly, are farmers.

00:40:29.200 --> 00:40:30.780
And you start to
drill down into that

00:40:30.780 --> 00:40:33.540
and you look at who has the most
nutrition insecure on the farm,

00:40:33.540 --> 00:40:35.620
it's women and children.

00:40:35.620 --> 00:40:39.360
So I don't have
brilliant answers for you

00:40:39.360 --> 00:40:43.170
on how to do this, but
if you look at SDG Two

00:40:43.170 --> 00:40:47.520
and even Google the
SDG Two Hub, you'll

00:40:47.520 --> 00:40:49.290
start to find some
really interesting work

00:40:49.290 --> 00:40:53.160
by amazing people, like
Ana's cohort group The Chef's

00:40:53.160 --> 00:40:55.560
Manifesto, that are
starting to try and put

00:40:55.560 --> 00:40:57.780
this whole thing together
and trying to figure out

00:40:57.780 --> 00:40:59.620
how do we challenge this.

00:40:59.620 --> 00:41:02.130
And the answer is, it's through
systems, and through systems

00:41:02.130 --> 00:41:02.910
transformation.

00:41:02.910 --> 00:41:05.560
And some of you-- all
of you can't see this,

00:41:05.560 --> 00:41:07.980
but there's a person
sitting in the front row

00:41:07.980 --> 00:41:11.070
here that has an amazing
patch on her coat

00:41:11.070 --> 00:41:12.528
that says break the routine.

00:41:12.528 --> 00:41:14.070
I think part of this
is, yeah we have

00:41:14.070 --> 00:41:16.080
to break to break the routine.

