00:41:43.600 --> 00:41:45.810
So part of it is
keeping food locally.

00:41:45.810 --> 00:41:49.500
Part of it is making sure that
food is properly refrigerated.

00:41:49.500 --> 00:41:52.860
New technologies are
helping that happen,

00:41:52.860 --> 00:41:55.710
so that you can get
food away from the farm

00:41:55.710 --> 00:42:00.990
and into our homes and
schools and supermarkets

00:42:00.990 --> 00:42:01.740
and everything.

00:42:01.740 --> 00:42:05.460
But part of it is you just have
to look at wherever you are.

00:42:05.460 --> 00:42:07.770
We talked about the home,
but talk about schools.

00:42:07.770 --> 00:42:09.240
You mentioned this, Walter.

00:42:09.240 --> 00:42:11.700
One of the things that the
Office of Sustainability

00:42:11.700 --> 00:42:15.390
here has not just done working
with the faculty, like Walter,

00:42:15.390 --> 00:42:17.970
and the students to
improve the quality

00:42:17.970 --> 00:42:19.950
of the food and the
nutritional value,

00:42:19.950 --> 00:42:22.200
but they're also
develop sustainability

00:42:22.200 --> 00:42:24.270
and healthful food
standards that

00:42:24.270 --> 00:42:26.770
look at where it's
coming from, and how

00:42:26.770 --> 00:42:30.180
I look at the full
lifecycle of the school.

00:42:30.180 --> 00:42:32.900
And it's available
online for other schools

00:42:32.900 --> 00:42:33.900
that want to look at it.

00:42:33.900 --> 00:42:38.140
It's at green.harvard.edu/food.

00:42:38.140 --> 00:42:41.910
It's a way to just
tell the students what

00:42:41.910 --> 00:42:46.320
the impact of this food is
so they can choose wisely.

00:42:46.320 --> 00:42:49.240
The more information we
have, the more transparent,

00:42:49.240 --> 00:42:52.240
the more you can make good
choices, and that's important.

00:42:52.240 --> 00:42:54.540
But when I was at
EPA we worked a lot

00:42:54.540 --> 00:42:57.000
with the James
Beard Society I went

00:42:57.000 --> 00:42:59.220
to a lot of their conferences
mainly because they

00:42:59.220 --> 00:43:03.120
had great food at them, but
mostly because we talked

00:43:03.120 --> 00:43:06.240
about these issues to get
people involved and engaged,

00:43:06.240 --> 00:43:08.900
to talk about food deserts
and where they are.

00:43:08.900 --> 00:43:10.640
Cities now can
manage those issues.

00:43:10.640 --> 00:43:13.850
They can demand that
supermarkets go in places where

00:43:13.850 --> 00:43:15.020
people need them most.

00:43:15.020 --> 00:43:16.970
One of the most
heartbreaking issues

00:43:16.970 --> 00:43:20.420
I had to deal with it
at EPA was the lead

00:43:20.420 --> 00:43:22.310
in the water in Flint, Michigan.

00:43:22.310 --> 00:43:24.620
When I went, there
every street corner

00:43:24.620 --> 00:43:29.180
had nothing but a small
little five and dime

00:43:29.180 --> 00:43:31.370
store, a little
store where you could

00:43:31.370 --> 00:43:34.040
buy cigarettes and a place
where you could buy liquor.

00:43:34.040 --> 00:43:36.570
I couldn't find a supermarket.

00:43:36.570 --> 00:43:39.920
Now, granted, the city
now has in its midst

00:43:39.920 --> 00:43:43.800
a really nice sort
of a farmer's market,

00:43:43.800 --> 00:43:46.880
but we have to address
these inequity issues.

00:43:46.880 --> 00:43:48.530
There's no question about it.

00:43:48.530 --> 00:43:49.850
And we can do that.

00:43:49.850 --> 00:43:51.980
We can demand more
of businesses.

00:43:51.980 --> 00:43:55.490
We can work in our
schools to make sure

00:43:55.490 --> 00:43:58.400
that one of the things they do
is talk at a lot of colleges.

00:43:58.400 --> 00:44:02.240
What schools have figured out
is if you don't put trays out,

00:44:02.240 --> 00:44:05.270
people don't throw food
away, because trays just

00:44:05.270 --> 00:44:07.770
allow you to pile stuff on
that you're never going to eat,

00:44:07.770 --> 00:44:09.560
but it looks good at the time.

00:44:09.560 --> 00:44:11.330
Sort of how we always act.

00:44:11.330 --> 00:44:13.010
Take the trays away.

00:44:13.010 --> 00:44:15.830
30% of the waste goes away.

00:44:15.830 --> 00:44:18.610
There's tricks to
dealing with human beings

00:44:18.610 --> 00:44:21.230
because we're all
kind of quirky, right?

00:44:21.230 --> 00:44:22.730
And then the other
thing we did is

00:44:22.730 --> 00:44:24.620
work with supermarkets,
first of all,

00:44:24.620 --> 00:44:27.180
in how they purchase their food.

00:44:27.180 --> 00:44:29.540
They overbought,
often, food that

00:44:29.540 --> 00:44:31.910
was going to be perishable.

00:44:31.910 --> 00:44:34.940
And then when the food
didn't look spiffy pretty,

00:44:34.940 --> 00:44:38.800
they'd toss it away, instead
of sharing it and sending it

00:44:38.800 --> 00:44:42.470
to other places, like
food pantries or soup

00:44:42.470 --> 00:44:46.520
kitchens, that can really
make something of this food.

00:44:46.520 --> 00:44:49.880
So there's ways in which we
can think creatively about this

00:44:49.880 --> 00:44:53.990
and not make everything so
hard, instead of integrate it

00:44:53.990 --> 00:44:56.450
into our lives in
an everyday way.

00:44:56.450 --> 00:44:59.990
It is only when you really start
to do that you get the breadth

00:44:59.990 --> 00:45:04.010
and depth of actions that
are essential for our future

00:45:04.010 --> 00:45:05.840
and our kids health.

00:45:05.840 --> 00:45:09.320
But when you do that, it becomes
ingrained in your own values

00:45:09.320 --> 00:45:12.620
and your own behavior,
and it matters.

00:45:12.620 --> 00:45:14.540
And the last thing
I wanted to mention

00:45:14.540 --> 00:45:17.840
is that I want to make sure
I don't leave oceans out,

00:45:17.840 --> 00:45:19.820
because we talk
about soil a lot.

00:45:19.820 --> 00:45:22.850
Not particularly
as relevant there.

00:45:22.850 --> 00:45:26.310
But there is significant
challenge with our oceans

00:45:26.310 --> 00:45:26.810
today.

00:45:26.810 --> 00:45:29.780
We now know that our
fisheries are being depleted,

00:45:29.780 --> 00:45:32.420
not just because
of coral bleaching,

00:45:32.420 --> 00:45:38.270
but because of the salinity
change in the oceans.

00:45:38.270 --> 00:45:42.170
And a lot of it has to do with
the ancillary issues related

00:45:42.170 --> 00:45:48.120
to our lives, like plastics that
are ending up in our bodies,

00:45:48.120 --> 00:45:52.190
in our blood, in our food,
the micro beads that happen.

00:45:52.190 --> 00:45:54.560
We have to think
more systemically

00:45:54.560 --> 00:45:55.820
about these issues.

00:45:55.820 --> 00:46:00.380
We cannot allow the sort of
things we use around our food

00:46:00.380 --> 00:46:02.970
to actually end
up in our bodies.

00:46:02.970 --> 00:46:06.750
And so there's a lot of work to
be done in that area, as well.

00:46:06.750 --> 00:46:10.448
And I think it's part and parcel
of the discussion we're having.

00:46:10.448 --> 00:46:12.240
DAVID FREEMAN: OK we're
