00:48:43.625 --> 00:48:45.500
can we achieve feeding
the world's population

00:48:45.500 --> 00:48:49.290
with organic
production principles?

00:48:49.290 --> 00:48:51.460
You want to take that or Gina?

00:48:51.460 --> 00:48:54.590
WALTER WILLETT: Yeah, we did
look at this in our report,

00:48:54.590 --> 00:48:58.020
our commission report where we
had agricultural experts there.

00:48:58.020 --> 00:49:02.420
And I think with today
we would probably

00:49:02.420 --> 00:49:05.480
not be able to feed the
world with 100% organic,

00:49:05.480 --> 00:49:08.930
but really applaud and encourage
every effort to produce food

00:49:08.930 --> 00:49:10.060
in a more organic way.

00:49:10.060 --> 00:49:15.360
It's not just a yes/no answer,
but reducing our insecticides,

00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:17.580
herbicides,
agricultural chemicals

00:49:17.580 --> 00:49:21.920
is very possible by
employing organic principles.

00:49:21.920 --> 00:49:24.170
I think one of the
biggest constraints

00:49:24.170 --> 00:49:28.340
is having enough nitrogen
fertilizer for parts of Africa

00:49:28.340 --> 00:49:31.350
where yields are extremely low.

00:49:31.350 --> 00:49:34.830
The long term solution will
involve some organic practices,

00:49:34.830 --> 00:49:37.970
but in the interim, at
least maybe in the long run,

00:49:37.970 --> 00:49:41.180
some modest amounts of
non-organic fertilizer

00:49:41.180 --> 00:49:43.820
probably will be required.

00:49:43.820 --> 00:49:48.330
So again trying to move in that
direction as much as we can

00:49:48.330 --> 00:49:52.320
is highly desirable, and
we should learn from that,

00:49:52.320 --> 00:49:55.370
but just a quick switch
to 100% organic today

00:49:55.370 --> 00:49:56.822
is probably not feasible.

